"England","Denton, Lancashire, England":"Denton, Lancashire, England","Worsley, Lancashire, England":"Worsley, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Wardley, Lancashire, England":"Wardley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wardley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Wardley (Rutland). Some of the bearers cited here may belong to (2), (3), or (4).","2  English: locative name from Wardley near Swinton in Worsley (Lancs).","3  English: locative name perhaps occasionally from Wardley in Iping (Sussex)."],"variants":[{"name":"Wardlow","meanings":["English: habitational name from Wardlow in Derbyshire, from Old English <i>weard</i> ‘watch’ + <i>hlāw</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Wardlaw  ."]},{"name":"Warley","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more places so named, such as Great and Little Warley (Essex), Warley Salop and Warley Wigorn (Worcestershire), Warley (Yorkshire), Warleigh in Bathford (Somerset), and Warleigh House in Tamerton Foliot (Devon). The Essex and Somerset placenames derive from Old English <i>wer</i>, <i>wær</i> ‘weir’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The Worcestershire placename may derive from a lost stream-name (of uncertain origin) or Old English <i>weorf</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>lēah</i>. The Yorkshire placename probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wērlāf</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i>. The Devon placename probably derives from Old English <i>weard</i> ‘watch’ + <i>lēah</i>. There may have been some confusion with   Worley   and   Whaley  ."]},{"name":"Wordley","meanings":["English: variant of   Wardley  . Compare William Wordley, 1608, Henry Wardley, 1661 in   IGI   (Nantwich, Cheshire)."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":5,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":40,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Yea